==English==

===Etymology===
{{etyl|ang}} {{term|becuman}}, from {{proto|Germanic}}.  Cognate with German {{term|bekommen}}, Dutch {{term|bekomen}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/bəˈkʌm/|/bɪˈkʌm/}}, {{SAMPA|/b@"kVm, bI"kVm/}}
* {{audio|en-us-become.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|ʌm}}
* {{hyphenation|be|come}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|becomes|becoming|'''[[became]]''', ''or (nonstandard)'' '''[[becomed]]'''|become}}

# {{intransitive|obsolete}} To [[arrive]], [[come]] (to a place). {{defdate|9th-18th c.}}
#* '''1485''', Sir Thomas Malory, ''Le Morte Darthur'', Book VII:
#*: And than Sir Launcelot departed suddeynly, and no creature wyst where he was '''becom''' but Sir Bors.
# {{context|copulative}} To [[begin]] to [[be]]; to come to be; to [[turn into]]. {{defdate|from 12th c.}}
#: ''She '''became''' a doctor when she was 25.''
#: ''The weather will '''become''' cold after the sun goes down.''
# {{transitive}} To look [[attractive]] on, be [[suitable]] for. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}
#: ''That dress really '''becomes''' you.''

